data.value:
The history of the city of Ioannina The city of Ioannina is built on the western shore of Lake Pamvotis, in the center of the basin defined by the Mitsikeli, Tomaros, and Xirovouni mountains. It is the capital of Epirus, a picturesque city steeped in culture, combining a long history with social, cultural, and economic activity and prosperity. It is a magnet and point of reference for many visitors. At the heart of the city lies the historic center with its beautiful pedestrian streets, the old town within the castle, and the lakeside area. The city was founded in the 6th century by the Byzantine Emperor Justinian. It was first mentioned by its current name in 879 and was the seat of a bishop. In 1789, the city became the seat of the region (pasaliki) controlled by Ali Pasha. During his reign, it reached the height of its prosperity. Since then, the expression “Ioannina first in chariots, coins, and letters” has remained well known. With the establishment of the University, which is one of the best in Europe, in 1970, as well as two hospitals, an international airport, and major road networks, Egnatia and Ionian Road, it has become one of the most attractive and developing cities in Greece.
A 365-day destination The city of Ioannina and its wider region is a place full of traditions, legends, and beautiful options for tours that cater to every taste. Seven amazing museums, a unique cave, the lake - the trademark of the entire valley. Walks through the picturesque alleys of the pedestrianized old town and the castle, lakeside strolls, hiking in the mountains, in the famous Vikos Gorge in Zagori and in the proud Tzoumerka. The options are truly endless and vary from season to season, making Ioannina a fantastic destination, regardless of the time of year. Multicultural, traditional, and inexhaustible! Ioannina has been a multicultural territory for centuries, with Christian, Islamic, and Jewish elements dominating, a coexistence that has left its mark on the historic center of the city.
Dozens of attractions The legendary lake of Ioannina is uniquely beautiful. Even more beautiful is the small island in the lake, one of the few inhabited lake islands in Europe, a place that has never been given another name, simply called The Island. There is also a collection of ecclesiastical monuments, which made the Island the third monastic state, after Mount Athos and Meteora, during the Byzantine period. Of particular cultural significance are the city's museums: the Archaeological Museum, the Byzantine Museum, the Municipal Museum, the Folklore Museum, the Silversmithing Museum, the Pavlos Vrellis Wax Museum, the Ali Pasha Museum of the Revolutionary Period, and the Municipal Art Gallery. Just outside the city of Ioannina, only 4 kilometers away, is the Perama Cave, one of the most beautiful caves in Europe, with a history dating back 1.5 million years. The Ancient Theater of Dodona is only 22 kilometers from the city of Ioannina, while the two mountainous areas of incomparable beauty, Zagorochoria and Tzoumerka, 40 kilometers away, are also worth mentioning.
Dining - entertainment In the city of Ioannina, there are plenty of taverns, luxury restaurants, grill houses, wine bars, ouzo bars, etc. In every area of Ioannina, you will find many options with traditional and European flavors, dishes cooked with local, high-quality ingredients, artistry, and aromas that add a unique experience for the visitor. At the same time, there are excellent pastry shops, traditional bakeries, and places for quick and good food every few meters. Of course, don't miss the famous tsipouro taverns, with the traditional tsipouro of the villages of the Ioannina region, without aniseed, and the wonderful local wine, for another form of midday or nighttime tasting and entertainment.
